{"cursor":"25124","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{infobox company\n| name = Asia Pulp & Paper logo = caption = Company's logo type = Produce &\n| trade genre = fate = predecessor = successor = foundation = founder = Eka\n| Cipta Widjaja defunct = location_city = location_country = locations =\n| area_served = key_people = industry = Paper & pulp products = services =\n| revenue = operating_income = net_income = aum = assets = equity = owner =\n| num_employees = parent = divisions = subsid = homepage =\n| [http://www.asiapulppaper.com/ asiapulppaper.com] footnotes = intl =\n}} 'Asia Pulp & Paper', also known in the paper industry as APP, based in\nSingapore, is one of the largest pulp and paper companies in the world. It was\nfounded by Eka Tjipta Widjaja, who had significant ties to the Suharto ruling\nfamily in Indonesia. APP claims to obtain 80â90% of the fibre for papermaking\nfrom sustainable plantations. \"ProPrint Webcast: A indÃºstria de papel e\ncelulose IndonÃ©sia pode ser sustentÃ¡vel?,\" interview with Aida Greenbury,\n[http://www.appbrasil.com.br/noticias/0035.htm] Many organisations have\ndocumented that a significant portion of its raw materials come from rainforests\nin addition to plantation wood. APP claims it is now working actively to rely on\nsustainable plantations for future production. \"A Voice of Nature: A\nPresentation of Remarkable Indonesia,\" Asia Pulp and Paper, April 2010.\n\nIt can produce about 2 million tons of pulp and more than 5 million tons of\npaper and packaging materials per year. Part of the Sinar Mas Group, it operates\nplants in Indonesia and China and sells to clients in more than 60 countries\naround the world.\n","linknr":282,"url":"Asia_Pulp_&_Paper","recorded":1374520536,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Asia_Pulp_%26_Paper&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Asia_Pulp_%26_Paper&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rs